                            <comment id="69073" author="schlaufuchs" created="Thu, 4 Aug 2011 22:34:02 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I&apos;ve attached a test project with a single JUnit class TestSPR8582.java This just shows the problem situation, not the workaround described above.&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="69091" author="cbeams" created="Fri, 5 Aug 2011 13:41:00 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;Hi Kai,&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Please see the the commit linked below for a full explanation of the problem you&apos;re seeing as well as additional suggestions for workarounds: &lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/SpringSource/spring-framework-issues/commit/4ea27b64420078b5514d950d2f6212a8a0b16f02&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow&quot;&gt;https://github.com/SpringSource/spring-framework-issues/commit/4ea27b64420078b5514d950d2f6212a8a0b16f02&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;</comment>
                            <comment id="69093" author="schlaufuchs" created="Fri, 5 Aug 2011 14:47:24 +0000"  >&lt;p&gt;I like the solution with injecting the parameters in the bean method. How does that work with beans of the same type? In our case we don&apos;t have qualifier to discriminate them but use autowiring by name. How would I annotate that?&lt;/p&gt;
</comment>
